The paper deals with triangulations of point sets in the Euclidean plane, which is a classic topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The problem of minimizing the number of edge flips to transform one triangulation to another is a combinatorial optimization problem, which falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the complexity of the problem, which involves analyzing the structure of the triangulations and their flips, and hence can be classified under discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The problem of edge flips and triangulations is also related to graph theory (cs.CC) and geometric topology (cs.GT).
